ts -- tCHAPTER 10 What Joss-Stick Community? Issues in the Inventory and Interpretation of Intangible Cultural Heritage in Macau -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor a long time, silk, tea, sinocentrism, and eurocentrism made up a big patch of East Asian history. Simultaneously deviating from and complicating these tags, this edited volume reconstructs narratives from the periphery and considers marginal voices located beyond official archives as the centre of East Asian history. The lives of the Japanese Buddhist monks, Eastern Han local governors, Confucian scholars, Chinese coolies, Shanghainese tailors, Macau joss-stick makers, Hong Kong locals, and Cantonese working-class musicians featured in this collection provide us with a glimpse of how East Asia’s inhabitants braved, with versatility, the ripples of political centralization, cross-border movement, foreign imperialism, nationalism, and globalism that sprouted locally and universally. Demonstrating the rich texture of sources discovered through non-official pathways, the ten essays in this volume ultimately reveal the timeless interconnectedness of East Asia and the complex, non-uniform worldviews of its inhabitants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aHistory. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aEast Asia, historical sources, unofficial histories, marginal voices, archive.1 aChan, Catherine S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Catherine S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChik, Hin Ming Frankie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElias, Hajni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc